00:00:24.260 --> 00:00:28.320
So today we're going to continue
our discussion of the

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:30.990
perfectly competitive
market outcome.

00:00:30.990 --> 00:00:33.080
And remember, once again, where
we're coming from here.

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:35.140
We're trying to figure
out how firms

00:00:35.140 --> 00:00:36.740
decide how much to produce.

00:00:36.740 --> 00:00:41.410
We talked about the firm's
production decision in costs.

00:00:41.410 --> 00:00:43.220
Then we said how the firm
decides how much to produce is

00:00:43.220 --> 00:00:45.060
going to get dictated
by the market.

00:00:45.060 --> 00:00:46.640
We're going to talk about
different market structures.

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:49.640
We'll start with our benchmark
of perfect competition and

00:00:49.640 --> 00:00:51.410
then move on to some more
interesting and realistic

00:00:51.410 --> 00:00:52.970
cases next.

00:00:52.970 --> 00:00:55.270
Now, I just want to finish up
where we were last time.

00:00:55.270 --> 00:00:57.110
Remember last time we were
dealing with a firm that had a

00:00:57.110 --> 00:01:04.440
cost function of the form
10 plus 0.5q squared.

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:07.800
And if you remember, the key
condition we derived last time

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:10.900
for profit maximization with a
perfectly competitive firm is

00:01:10.900 --> 00:01:15.680
that price equals marginal cost.
If you differentiate

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:21.300
this with respect to q, you
get that that means that p

00:01:21.300 --> 00:01:25.150
equals q is the profit
maximizing

00:01:25.150 --> 00:01:26.850
condition for this firm.

00:01:26.850 --> 00:01:29.400
It sets the price equal to
quantity it's going to sell.

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:31.480
That's the profit maximizing
condition with this particular

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:33.940
functional form of the
cost function.

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:36.770
Now, before we left last time,
I said, this was not enough.

00:01:36.770 --> 00:01:38.960
There's one other thing you have
to consider which is the

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:40.350
firm's shutdown decision.

00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:49.620
In the short run, a firm might
not shut down even if it's

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:51.460
losing money.

00:01:51.460 --> 00:01:54.360
And the reason is because the
firm has already paid its

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:55.790
fixed costs.

00:01:55.790 --> 00:01:58.280
It's already paid 10.

00:01:58.280 --> 00:02:03.550
So even if it's losing money, it
might still not shut down.

00:02:03.550 --> 00:02:06.750
So, for example, imagine that
the price, as I said last

00:02:06.750 --> 00:02:09.862
time, imagine the price
fell from 6 to 3.

00:02:09.862 --> 00:02:12.130
The price equals 3.

00:02:12.130 --> 00:02:14.700
If the price equals 3, the firm
will choose to produce 3

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:16.710
units, because it will
still follow the

00:02:16.710 --> 00:02:18.830
profit maximizing condition.

00:02:18.830 --> 00:02:21.360
It will still choose to
produce three units.

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:25.660
If it produces 3 units,
its profits are its

00:02:25.660 --> 00:02:28.446
revenues which is 9--

00:02:28.446 --> 00:02:30.710
3 units at a price of 3--

00:02:30.710 --> 00:02:34.340
minus its cost which is 14.5.

00:02:34.340 --> 00:02:37.060
So that equals negative 5.5.

00:02:37.060 --> 00:02:39.680
So its profits are negative.

00:02:39.680 --> 00:02:42.250
So now I say, well, if profits
are negative, maybe I should

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:44.460
shut down and stop
doing business.

00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:48.670
Well, what are its profits
if it shuts down?

00:02:48.670 --> 00:02:49.460
Negative 10.

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:54.160
If it shuts down, its profits
are 0 minus 10

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:55.580
equals negative 10.

00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:58.060
So it actually makes more money
by staying in business

00:02:58.060 --> 00:03:02.290
than shutting down, because
it has these fixed costs.

00:03:02.290 --> 00:03:05.500
So because it's going to pay the
10 anyway, as long as it's

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:08.040
going to lose less than
10, it might as

00:03:08.040 --> 00:03:10.230
well stay in business.

00:03:10.230 --> 00:03:16.000
More generally, what we say is
a firm will stay in business

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:19.750
in the short run as long
as its price covers

00:03:19.750 --> 00:03:21.900
its variable costs.

00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:27.820
So a firm will stay in business
so long as the price

00:03:27.820 --> 00:03:31.760
is greater or equal to
its variable costs.

00:03:31.760 --> 00:03:33.010
Then it will stay in business.

00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:44.500
If we go further--

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:45.980
let me just derive it for a
second-- as long as they cover

00:03:45.980 --> 00:03:48.720
its fixed costs, that means a
firm will stay in business as

00:03:48.720 --> 00:03:52.330
long as its revenues
are greater than

00:03:52.330 --> 00:03:53.910
its variable costs.

00:03:53.910 --> 00:03:55.800
As long as its revenues are
greater than or equal to its

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:57.320
variable costs, it will
stay in business.

00:04:00.010 --> 00:04:02.246
And that means that it will stay
in business at long as

00:04:02.246 --> 00:04:04.540
its price is greater than or
equal-- this should be a

00:04:04.540 --> 00:04:06.470
little q, sorry, this
is just a firm--

00:04:06.470 --> 00:04:07.820
as long as its price is greater
than or equal to

00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:12.970
variable costs over quantity, or
as long as price is greater

00:04:12.970 --> 00:04:16.310
than or equal to average
variable cost.

00:04:16.310 --> 00:04:18.380
As long as its price is greater
than or equal to its

00:04:18.380 --> 00:04:23.100
average variable cost, it
will stay in business.

00:04:23.100 --> 00:04:26.440
As long as its revenues cover
its variable costs, it will

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:27.030
say in business.

00:04:27.030 --> 00:04:29.466
And that's saying the same as
long as its price is great

00:04:29.466 --> 00:04:31.045
than or equal to average
variable cost, it

00:04:31.045 --> 00:04:32.295
will stay in business.

00:04:34.930 --> 00:04:39.790
Now, what are the average
variable costs for our firm?

00:04:39.790 --> 00:04:42.880
Well, the variable costs
for our firm

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:47.410
are 0.5 times q squared.

00:04:47.410 --> 00:04:50.980
The variable costs for our firm
are 0.5 times q squared.

00:04:57.350 --> 00:05:00.510
We know that in equilibrium, if
it's profit maximizing, it

00:05:00.510 --> 00:05:02.950
will produce where q equals p.

00:05:02.950 --> 00:05:05.040
So we can replace the
q with the p.

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:08.320
The variable costs are 0.5 times
p squared, because we

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:11.000
know we'll produce
where q equals p.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:17.510
So its average variable
costs are 0.5 times p.

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:22.010
Its average variable costs
are 0.5 times p.

00:05:22.010 --> 00:05:24.490
Well, by definition,
p is always greater

00:05:24.490 --> 00:05:26.470
than 0.5 times p.

00:05:26.470 --> 00:05:30.440
So our firm will never go out of
business in the short run.

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:33.500
In the short run, our firm will
never go out of business,

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:37.900
because at the profit maximizing
price, at p equals

00:05:37.900 --> 00:05:42.460
q, it will always be producing
a point where the price is

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:45.066
greater than its average
variable cost. So it will

00:05:45.066 --> 00:05:47.880
never shut down.

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:50.580
So, more generally, when we
think about a short run supply

00:05:50.580 --> 00:05:52.550
decision, a short run supply
decision for a

00:05:52.550 --> 00:05:55.130
firm, there's two steps.

00:05:55.130 --> 00:05:59.260
The first step is set price
equal to marginal cost to

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:02.310
figure out what the firm
is going to produce.

00:06:02.310 --> 00:06:07.670
So step one is set price equal
to marginal cost. And that

00:06:07.670 --> 00:06:10.200
will give you the firm's q*.

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:13.550
That will give you what the
firm is going to produce.

00:06:13.550 --> 00:06:19.885
The second step is check that
price is greater than or equal

00:06:19.885 --> 00:06:21.210
to average variable costs.

00:06:21.210 --> 00:06:23.760
Because you may solve for an
optimal quantity that turns

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:25.110
out to be a money loser
for the firm.

00:06:25.110 --> 00:06:26.840
So they'd rather shut down.

00:06:26.840 --> 00:06:28.180
So it's a two-step process.

00:06:28.180 --> 00:06:30.024
You've got to first solve for
the optimal quantity that the

00:06:30.024 --> 00:06:32.100
firm is going to produce.

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:33.500
But then you've got to make sure
that the firm actually

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:37.190
makes money on that quantity,
or it won't produce at all.

00:06:37.190 --> 00:06:39.920
And that's how we do the profit
maximization decision

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:42.890
in the short run for the firm.

00:06:42.890 --> 00:06:45.520
You've got to produce at the
efficient point and make sure

00:06:45.520 --> 00:06:48.760
the firm actually makes
some money.

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:52.530
All right, questions
about that?

00:06:52.530 --> 00:06:57.600
Now, armed with these rules,
we can now, finally, derive

00:06:57.600 --> 00:06:59.280
the supply curve.

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:03.360
Remember we derived the demand
curve a number of lectures ago

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:08.540
by getting the tangency at
different price ratios with

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:09.690
the indifference curves.

00:07:09.690 --> 00:07:12.860
Well, to derive the firm's
supply function, what we now

00:07:12.860 --> 00:07:16.420
need to do is say, OK, at
different prices, how much

00:07:16.420 --> 00:07:17.760
will the firm produce?

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:21.000
Well, we can now get that
if we go to Figure 11-1.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.640
We can now see the supply
curve for this firm.

00:07:24.640 --> 00:07:28.060
What we see is that at a price
of 3, it will produce 3 units.

00:07:28.060 --> 00:07:31.310
At a price of 4, it will produce
4 units, et cetera.

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:35.860
The supply curve is the
marginal cost curve.

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:37.920
So now we know where supply
curves come from.

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:42.800
Supply curves are marginal cost
curves above the point

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:45.590
where price equals average
variable cost. So the

00:07:45.590 --> 00:07:51.540
definition of a firm's supply
curve is the marginal cost

00:07:51.540 --> 00:07:58.290
curve above p is greater than
or equal to average variable

00:07:58.290 --> 00:08:01.920
cost. That is the firm's
short run supply curve.

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:04.800
Now, in our case, p is always
greater than average variable

00:08:04.800 --> 00:08:07.940
cost. So the second condition
is irrelevant.

00:08:07.940 --> 00:08:09.750
The firm's supply curve is just
literally that marginal

00:08:09.750 --> 00:08:10.570
cost curve.

00:08:10.570 --> 00:08:13.170
With different functions, which
you may someday see in a

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:16.680
problem set or an exam,
that won't be true.

00:08:16.680 --> 00:08:18.800
So, in that case, you'll
need to check

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:21.380
that shutdown condition.

00:08:21.380 --> 00:08:25.880
But the supply curve is the
marginal cost curve above that

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:28.010
0 profit point.

00:08:28.010 --> 00:08:30.390
And that's where supply
curves come from.

00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:32.740
So where supply curves comes
from is the same kind of

00:08:32.740 --> 00:08:34.679
maximization we did
with consumers.

00:08:34.679 --> 00:08:39.200
But instead of their parents
giving them their income, the

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:41.460
market conditions firms face
are dictated by the

00:08:41.460 --> 00:08:44.440
competitive nature
of the market.

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:47.710
And that's the firm's
supply curve.

00:08:47.710 --> 00:08:52.560
Now, this is the firm's
supply curve.

00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:54.590
Now, of course, what we talked
about in the first lecture was

00:08:54.590 --> 00:08:57.770
not firm supply curves but
market supply curves.

00:08:57.770 --> 00:08:59.480
So now let's take the next step
and say, well, where do

00:08:59.480 --> 00:09:00.850
market supply curves
come from?

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:03.780
We now know where firm supply
curves come from.

00:09:03.780 --> 00:09:06.600
The marginal cost stork
brings them.

00:09:06.600 --> 00:09:09.640
Now, where do market supply
curves come from?

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:15.010
Well, to do that, we need to now
imagine that there's not

00:09:15.010 --> 00:09:19.230
one firm in the market but
many firms in the market.

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:25.080
And we need to recognize that
the market demand may not be

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:26.090
perfectly elastic.

00:09:26.090 --> 00:09:30.700
But, as we talked about last
time, the firm's own demand

00:09:30.700 --> 00:09:32.140
will be close to perfectly
elastic.

00:09:32.140 --> 00:09:33.835
Or, in this case, a perfect
competition will

00:09:33.835 --> 00:09:36.830
be perfectly elastic.

00:09:36.830 --> 00:09:44.590
So, basically, the way to get
market demand is to say, look,

00:09:44.590 --> 00:09:46.330
we're going to take each firm.

00:09:46.330 --> 00:09:48.195
It's going to take a market
price as given.

00:09:51.420 --> 00:09:52.490
I'm sorry, we get
market supply.

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:53.180
I'm sorry.

00:09:53.180 --> 00:09:56.030
Each firm is going to take
a market price as given.

00:09:56.030 --> 00:09:58.110
Based on that market price, it's
going to decide how much

00:09:58.110 --> 00:09:59.690
to produce.

00:09:59.690 --> 00:10:01.850
We're going to add up
that production.

00:10:01.850 --> 00:10:05.360
That will make a market
supply curve.

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:07.570
And that market supply curve
will then interact with market

00:10:07.570 --> 00:10:09.750
demand to give you a price.

00:10:09.750 --> 00:10:12.830
If that price is the same one
the firms were using, then the

00:10:12.830 --> 00:10:15.000
whole thing is in equilibrium.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:19.320
Let me explain that in less
steps just to make it clear.

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:23.190
Let's talk about the steps
involved in getting to short

00:10:23.190 --> 00:10:27.952
run equilibrium in the market,
the steps involved in getting

00:10:27.952 --> 00:10:31.400
to short run market
equilibrium.

00:10:31.400 --> 00:10:36.000
The first step is each firm
chooses an amount of capital.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.490
So the first step of the short
run is you're going to enter

00:10:38.490 --> 00:10:39.450
this market.

00:10:39.450 --> 00:10:41.370
And to enter this market, you're
going to have an amount

00:10:41.370 --> 00:10:43.860
of capital you're
going to pick.

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:49.410
So each firm is going to have
some cost function which

00:10:49.410 --> 00:10:52.500
involves picking some amount
of capital or fixed costs.

00:10:57.040 --> 00:10:59.070
It's going to say, I want to
build a building this big.

00:11:03.350 --> 00:11:05.670
Having built that building,
we're going to get the firm's

00:11:05.670 --> 00:11:12.050
supply curve which
is p equals MC.

00:11:14.650 --> 00:11:15.260
That's step one.

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:18.600
That's a step we've derived.

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:23.690
The second step is we're going
to add up the firm's supply

00:11:23.690 --> 00:11:30.140
curves to get a market
supply curve.

00:11:33.040 --> 00:11:35.610
We're going to add up the firm's
supply curve to get a

00:11:35.610 --> 00:11:37.570
market supply curve.

00:11:37.570 --> 00:11:41.640
So, for example, suppose
that there's five

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:42.890
firms in the market.

00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:50.750
Suppose that there's five
firms in the market.

00:11:53.530 --> 00:11:56.740
Those five firms are
going to produce.

00:11:56.740 --> 00:12:01.120
Now to see that, let's
go to Figure 11-2.

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:02.740
This is the second step.

00:12:02.740 --> 00:12:06.180
It's how we get to that short
run market supply curve.

00:12:06.180 --> 00:12:09.600
Each firm has a marginal
cost curve.

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:13.320
Here we're using our same cost
function we've used.

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:15.340
That same cost function up
there where price equals

00:12:15.340 --> 00:12:18.980
marginal cost, where p equals
q, is the supply curve.

00:12:18.980 --> 00:12:20.900
So each firm has that
supply curve you see

00:12:20.900 --> 00:12:22.570
in the first panel.

00:12:22.570 --> 00:12:27.220
Then what you see is as you
add more firms, the second

00:12:27.220 --> 00:12:28.720
panel gives you the market
supply curve.

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:31.280
So if there's only one firm in
the market, the market supply

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:33.940
curve would be S1.

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:36.600
Now, if there were two firms
in the market, the market

00:12:36.600 --> 00:12:37.460
supply curve is S2.

00:12:37.460 --> 00:12:40.770
That is, at a price of 2, you're
now producing 4 units

00:12:40.770 --> 00:12:42.020
in the market.

00:12:42.020 --> 00:12:45.180
If there's three firms,
the curve is S3, four

00:12:45.180 --> 00:12:46.980
firms, S4, and so on.

00:12:46.980 --> 00:12:51.850
As you add more firms, that
market supply curve shifts out

00:12:51.850 --> 00:12:55.070
and becomes flatter.

00:12:55.070 --> 00:12:56.730
Remember firms are
identical here.

00:12:56.730 --> 00:12:58.380
We're adding identical firms.
That was an assumption of

00:12:58.380 --> 00:12:59.300
perfect competition.

00:12:59.300 --> 00:13:01.340
We're adding more and
more identical firms

00:13:01.340 --> 00:13:02.430
producing the same good.

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:06.120
You can see that market supply
curve is shifting out and

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:08.170
becoming flatter.

00:13:08.170 --> 00:13:13.500
That is the supply of goods is
becoming more elastic as there

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:17.960
are more firms. The more firms
in the market the more elastic

00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:18.530
the supply.

00:13:18.530 --> 00:13:20.820
And that comes to what we talked
about last time when I

00:13:20.820 --> 00:13:22.070
derived residual demand.

00:13:25.106 --> 00:13:27.120
It's sort of the flip
side of that.

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:29.850
Basically, the more firms you
have with a given supply curve

00:13:29.850 --> 00:13:32.610
in the market, the more elastic
it's going to become.

00:13:32.610 --> 00:13:33.640
Why is that?

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:35.115
Well, just think about it.

00:13:35.115 --> 00:13:37.150
Think about what elasticity
of supply is.

00:13:37.150 --> 00:13:40.000
It's saying, if I increase the
price by $1, how much more

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.110
production do I call forth?

00:13:42.110 --> 00:13:44.920
Well, the more identical firms
I have, every time I increase

00:13:44.920 --> 00:13:47.970
the price by $1, I call forth
production from all these

00:13:47.970 --> 00:13:50.840
firms. So the more firms I have,
the more production I

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:52.010
call forth.

00:13:52.010 --> 00:13:54.700
So for every increment in price,
the more firms in the

00:13:54.700 --> 00:13:56.840
market, the more production
I call forth.

00:13:56.840 --> 00:14:00.380
Therefore, the more elastic
is the supply.

00:14:00.380 --> 00:14:03.330
So as there are more firms,
that market supply curve

00:14:03.330 --> 00:14:05.670
becomes more and more elastic.

00:14:05.670 --> 00:14:06.970
And that's the market
supply curve.

00:14:06.970 --> 00:14:10.150
That's the second step.

00:14:10.150 --> 00:14:23.880
The third step is we intersect
market supply with market

00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:29.450
demand to get the equilibrium
price.

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:36.900
So, in other words, we say,
look, there's some market

00:14:36.900 --> 00:14:38.900
supply, which we've derived.

00:14:38.900 --> 00:14:41.160
Now let's imagine there's
some market demand.

00:14:41.160 --> 00:14:43.240
And that will give us the
equilibrium price.

00:14:43.240 --> 00:14:51.510
So, for example, in our case,
market supply is what?

00:14:54.850 --> 00:14:56.230
Let's say, for example,
there's five

00:14:56.230 --> 00:14:56.850
firms in the market.

00:14:56.850 --> 00:14:59.120
Just to make an example, let's
say five firms have entered.

00:14:59.120 --> 00:15:00.970
There's five firms
in the market.

00:15:00.970 --> 00:15:06.710
Well, the total market supply
Q is 5 of the little q,

00:15:06.710 --> 00:15:10.290
because there's five identical
firms in the market.

00:15:10.290 --> 00:15:12.240
Five identical firms
are in the market.

00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:15.160
Well, we know, from the marginal
cost condition,

00:15:15.160 --> 00:15:18.450
that's the same as saying
Q equals 5 times p.

00:15:18.450 --> 00:15:22.200
So our market supply curve,
which is actually S5 on Figure

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:24.940
11-2, is Q equals 5p.

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:25.400
You can see that.

00:15:25.400 --> 00:15:27.860
Because when the price
is 2, Q equals 10.

00:15:27.860 --> 00:15:34.180
When the price is
5, Q equals 25.

00:15:34.180 --> 00:15:37.980
So you can see that S super 5
is the market supply curve.

00:15:37.980 --> 00:15:39.230
Big Q equals 5p.

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:44.260
Let's just make this up.

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:46.290
So this is the quantity
supplied.

00:15:46.290 --> 00:15:51.280
Let's say the demand function is
that the quantity demanded

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:54.930
is 30 minus p.

00:15:54.930 --> 00:15:56.470
I just made this up.

00:15:56.470 --> 00:15:57.370
I'm making all this up.

00:15:57.370 --> 00:15:59.550
But this is just an example
demand curve.

00:15:59.550 --> 00:16:03.430
We have a downward sloping
demand curve with a slope of

00:16:03.430 --> 00:16:05.080
negative 1.

00:16:05.080 --> 00:16:08.020
The quantity demanded
is 30 minus p.

00:16:08.020 --> 00:16:12.450
So to get equilibrium,
we set these equal.

00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:20.610
And we get that 30 minus p
equals 5p or p equals 5.

00:16:23.330 --> 00:16:28.830
30 minus p equals 5p or
p equals 5, that's the

00:16:28.830 --> 00:16:30.460
equilibrium price.

00:16:30.460 --> 00:16:34.470
Given the market supply curve,
given the demand curve, I've

00:16:34.470 --> 00:16:36.695
derived the equilibrium
price of 5.

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:43.170
Now, at a price of 5, what's
the quantity demanded?

00:16:43.170 --> 00:16:46.840
At a price of 5, quantity
demanded equals 25.

00:16:46.840 --> 00:16:50.340
So, at a price of 5, the market
wants 25 of these

00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:51.980
things, whatever the heck
it's producing.

00:16:51.980 --> 00:16:55.960
At a price of 5, the market
wants 25 of them.

00:16:55.960 --> 00:16:58.520
That's the quantity demanded.

00:16:58.520 --> 00:17:05.270
Then the final step in solving
for equilibrium is that each

00:17:05.270 --> 00:17:07.595
firm then decides how
much to produce.

00:17:21.930 --> 00:17:24.150
Well, what is each firm going
to decide to produce?

00:17:24.150 --> 00:17:26.630
How much is each firm going
to decide to produce?

00:17:26.630 --> 00:17:28.590
Somebody raise their
hand and tell me.

00:17:28.590 --> 00:17:29.213
Yeah.

00:17:29.213 --> 00:17:29.980
AUDIENCE: p.

00:17:29.980 --> 00:17:30.740
PROFESSOR: p which is?

00:17:30.740 --> 00:17:31.150
AUDIENCE: 5

00:17:31.150 --> 00:17:31.415
PROFESSOR: 5.

00:17:31.415 --> 00:17:33.710
So each firm is going
to produce 5.

00:17:33.710 --> 00:17:35.260
How many firms are there?

00:17:35.260 --> 00:17:35.750
AUDIENCE: 5.

00:17:35.750 --> 00:17:36.820
PROFESSOR: How much
gets produced?

00:17:36.820 --> 00:17:37.215
AUDIENCE: 25.

00:17:37.215 --> 00:17:38.890
PROFESSOR: Which is exactly
what people want.

00:17:38.890 --> 00:17:41.020
We're done.

00:17:41.020 --> 00:17:43.840
That's the magic
of the market.

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:45.950
Through these four steps, we've
gotten equilibrium which

00:17:45.950 --> 00:17:47.860
is defined as the quantity
supplied equals the quantity

00:17:47.860 --> 00:17:50.870
demanded, just by following
these steps.

00:17:50.870 --> 00:17:54.900
The firms didn't come at it
saying, hey, let's figure this

00:17:54.900 --> 00:17:57.290
out beforehand.

00:17:57.290 --> 00:17:59.310
Let's all get together and
coordinate and figure out how

00:17:59.310 --> 00:17:59.980
much we're going to produce
at what price.

00:17:59.980 --> 00:18:01.760
They didn't do that at all.

00:18:01.760 --> 00:18:04.550
The firms just entered
the market.

00:18:04.550 --> 00:18:07.010
They said, this is
my supply curve.

00:18:07.010 --> 00:18:08.330
We added it up.

00:18:08.330 --> 00:18:10.120
We interact it with demand.

00:18:10.120 --> 00:18:12.240
We find an equilibrium price.

00:18:12.240 --> 00:18:14.630
At that equilibrium price, the
quantity demanded equals the

00:18:14.630 --> 00:18:15.730
quantity supplied.

00:18:15.730 --> 00:18:16.980
We're done.

00:18:19.410 --> 00:18:23.290
We've now finally gotten to
where we started this course.

00:18:23.290 --> 00:18:25.650
We started this course with
a supply and demand graph.

00:18:25.650 --> 00:18:27.250
I told you how to
derive demand.

00:18:27.250 --> 00:18:29.360
You took a test on
that already.

00:18:29.360 --> 00:18:31.350
Now I've just told you where
supply comes from.

00:18:31.350 --> 00:18:32.760
Now we interact,
and we're done.

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:35.860
And this tells us now, given
this price, how much each firm

00:18:35.860 --> 00:18:37.110
is going to produce.

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:43.960
So, basically, what do you
need to find equilibrium?

00:18:43.960 --> 00:18:47.160
What do you need to find the
short run equilibrium?

00:18:47.160 --> 00:18:49.780
To find the short run
equilibrium, you need a demand

00:18:49.780 --> 00:18:56.790
function, a cost function, and a
number of firms. You have to

00:18:56.790 --> 00:18:58.840
be given a number firms, because
there's no entry and

00:18:58.840 --> 00:19:00.380
exit in the short
run, remember.

00:19:00.380 --> 00:19:03.220
So, basically, the firms are
magically put on the earth in

00:19:03.220 --> 00:19:04.400
the short run.

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:07.230
So if you're asked about the
short run equilibrium, you

00:19:07.230 --> 00:19:08.420
have to be given the number
of firms. You

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:10.120
can't derive that yet.

00:19:10.120 --> 00:19:11.270
That comes in the long run.

00:19:11.270 --> 00:19:14.100
But given a number of firms,
given a cost function, and

00:19:14.100 --> 00:19:17.310
given the demand function, you
can find the short run

00:19:17.310 --> 00:19:19.360
equilibrium.

00:19:19.360 --> 00:19:20.610
Questions about that?

00:19:23.400 --> 00:19:26.460
Now, with that in place, now
let's get to where it gets

00:19:26.460 --> 00:19:27.440
really interesting.

00:19:27.440 --> 00:19:29.640
Let's talk now about
the long run.

00:19:29.640 --> 00:19:31.830
Now what makes the long run
interesting is you no longer

00:19:31.830 --> 00:19:35.750
have to be given the number of
firms. Now, in the long run,

00:19:35.750 --> 00:19:37.800
we're going to actually
figure out how many

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:39.510
firms are in the market.

00:19:39.510 --> 00:19:41.765
So at the end of the day, in the
long run, all we'll need

00:19:41.765 --> 00:19:44.170
is two things, a demand function
and a cost function.

00:19:44.170 --> 00:19:46.640
And then we'll be done.

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:49.310
Now, here's the key thing
for the long run.

00:19:49.310 --> 00:19:51.630
The key point in the long run
is that in the long run, no

00:19:51.630 --> 00:19:53.290
one can lose money.

00:19:53.290 --> 00:19:54.170
So we don't have to
worry about the

00:19:54.170 --> 00:19:56.030
shutdown condition anymore.

00:19:56.030 --> 00:19:57.330
The shutdown condition
goes away.

00:19:57.330 --> 00:20:00.200
In the long run, nothing
is fixed.

00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:02.400
So in the long run, no
one loses money.

00:20:02.400 --> 00:20:04.560
There's no reason to be in the
market if you're losing money

00:20:04.560 --> 00:20:06.840
in the long run.

00:20:06.840 --> 00:20:09.520
So, in long run, the first thing
is now we only have one

00:20:09.520 --> 00:20:12.890
condition to worry about, which
is price equals marginal

00:20:12.890 --> 00:20:17.930
cost. Price equals marginal
cost is what we

00:20:17.930 --> 00:20:19.180
need to worry about.

00:20:25.870 --> 00:20:28.680
And you're only going to be in
a situation, in the long run,

00:20:28.680 --> 00:20:30.570
where you're only going
to be making either

00:20:30.570 --> 00:20:31.810
0 or positive profits.

00:20:31.810 --> 00:20:35.170
If you're making negative
profits, you'll be gone.

00:20:35.170 --> 00:20:39.180
Now, the key difference in the
long run, is now we can't take

00:20:39.180 --> 00:20:40.810
the number of firms as given.

00:20:40.810 --> 00:20:43.450
Now we need to derive the number
of firms. And the way

00:20:43.450 --> 00:20:47.920
we do that is by thinking
about entry and exit.

00:20:47.920 --> 00:20:50.060
Now, what's going to determine
entry and exit?

00:20:50.060 --> 00:20:51.970
Well, it's quite simple.

00:20:51.970 --> 00:20:56.160
If in the market, as it stands
today with some number of

00:20:56.160 --> 00:21:01.190
firms, there's profit to be
made, new firms will enter.

00:21:01.190 --> 00:21:03.500
If in the market, as it stands
today with some number of

00:21:03.500 --> 00:21:07.000
firms, there's losses being
made, some firms will leave.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:09.490
Remember, no one stays in
making losses anymore.

00:21:09.490 --> 00:21:14.890
And that continues until you
reach a situation where all

00:21:14.890 --> 00:21:16.860
firms make zero profit.

00:21:16.860 --> 00:21:20.470
And here's the key lesson.

00:21:20.470 --> 00:21:27.040
In a perfectly competitive
long run equilibrium, all

00:21:27.040 --> 00:21:30.960
firms make zero profit.

00:21:34.700 --> 00:21:37.860
It's the fundamental lesson
about perfect competition.

00:21:37.860 --> 00:21:39.340
Obviously, there's no
place that works

00:21:39.340 --> 00:21:40.110
like this in the world.

00:21:40.110 --> 00:21:41.650
This is an extreme.

00:21:41.650 --> 00:21:43.420
But, nonetheless, you should
understand this extreme.

00:21:43.420 --> 00:21:45.090
In a perfectly competitive
long run equilibrium, all

00:21:45.090 --> 00:21:46.220
firms make zero profit.

00:21:46.220 --> 00:21:47.140
Why?

00:21:47.140 --> 00:21:49.810
Because if there's any profit
to be made, a new firm will

00:21:49.810 --> 00:21:51.770
enter and take it away.

00:21:51.770 --> 00:21:53.805
And if there's any unprofitable
industry, a firm

00:21:53.805 --> 00:21:56.780
will exit until the profits
go back to zero.

00:21:56.780 --> 00:22:02.130
So profits will always be zero
in the long run equilibrium.

00:22:02.130 --> 00:22:06.910
Now, to understand how this
works, let's think about a

00:22:06.910 --> 00:22:07.730
realistic example.

00:22:07.730 --> 00:22:11.300
Let's think about the PC market
circa 1990 when all you

00:22:11.300 --> 00:22:13.196
youngins were being born.

00:22:13.196 --> 00:22:16.870
It's circa about 1990,
the PC market, cast

00:22:16.870 --> 00:22:18.180
your mind way back.

00:22:18.180 --> 00:22:20.710
It's a history lesson
for you guys.

00:22:20.710 --> 00:22:27.220
In 1990, not that many
folks had PCs.

00:22:27.220 --> 00:22:31.190
There was still a vibrant use
of mainframe computers.

