00:27:04.540 --> 00:27:05.370
I have no choice.

00:27:05.370 --> 00:27:08.600
That's what's profit
maximizing.

00:27:08.600 --> 00:27:10.660
I can't choose a point not on
that marginal cost curve.

00:27:10.660 --> 00:27:12.370
That will not be profit
maximizing.

00:27:12.370 --> 00:27:14.790
Well, where does that
price intersect that

00:27:14.790 --> 00:27:15.930
marginal cost curve?

00:27:15.930 --> 00:27:17.390
At little q2.

00:27:17.390 --> 00:27:18.510
So I'm producing at little q2.

00:27:18.510 --> 00:27:21.240
And at little q2, I
make no profit.

00:27:21.240 --> 00:27:23.730
So the entry of Gateway and
other firms into the PC

00:27:23.730 --> 00:27:29.720
business has removed the profit
from the PC business.

00:27:29.720 --> 00:27:31.700
Now note what's interesting
here.

00:27:31.700 --> 00:27:34.940
Market quantity has gone up.

00:27:34.940 --> 00:27:37.540
Big Q2 is bigger than big Q1.

00:27:37.540 --> 00:27:39.910
But Dell's quantity
has gone down.

00:27:39.910 --> 00:27:42.310
Little q2 is smaller
than little q1.

00:27:42.310 --> 00:27:44.730
That's because more firms are
in the market producing.

00:27:44.730 --> 00:27:47.600
So as more firms come in, total
market quantity goes up.

00:27:47.600 --> 00:27:50.110
But any given firm is going
to produce less.

00:27:50.110 --> 00:27:54.290
And that will continue until
profits go to zero.

00:27:54.290 --> 00:27:58.150
That is how firm entry
wipes out profits.

00:27:58.150 --> 00:28:02.970
That is how firm entry wipes out
profits, by driving firms

00:28:02.970 --> 00:28:08.000
to the point where price
equals average cost.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:11.900
So, in the long run, firms
make zero profit because,

00:28:11.900 --> 00:28:20.720
first of all, entry drives price
down to average cost.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:23.730
Entry drives price down to
average cost. And when price

00:28:23.730 --> 00:28:27.290
equals average cost,
profits are zero.

00:28:27.290 --> 00:28:28.790
Profits are zero when price
equals average cost. Because

00:28:28.790 --> 00:28:35.670
profits are pq minus C. So if
you divide by qp profits are p

00:28:35.670 --> 00:28:37.040
minus average costs.

00:28:37.040 --> 00:28:40.360
So if price equals average
cost, profits are zero.

00:28:40.360 --> 00:28:42.230
So entry drives profits
to zero.

00:28:42.230 --> 00:28:45.760
It drives price to equal average
cost. Since price

00:28:45.760 --> 00:28:48.720
equals marginal cost, it's the
point where marginal cost

00:28:48.720 --> 00:28:54.410
equals average cost. That's the
technological outcome in a

00:28:54.410 --> 00:28:57.000
perfectly competitive long
run equilibrium.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:28:59.610
You'll end up producing where
marginal cost equals average

00:28:59.610 --> 00:29:02.750
cost. That's what will end up
happening naturally through

00:29:02.750 --> 00:29:04.000
the forces of entry.

00:29:08.380 --> 00:29:12.220
Likewise, you see this through
the force of exit.

00:29:12.220 --> 00:29:13.990
Now let's go to Figure 11-4.

00:29:13.990 --> 00:29:15.240
And now let's look at IBM.

00:29:22.400 --> 00:29:24.430
I guess we're calling this the
broader computer market now.

00:29:24.430 --> 00:29:25.430
It's not just a PC market.

00:29:25.430 --> 00:29:26.680
It's the broader computer
market.

00:29:30.140 --> 00:29:35.670
So IBM, they're producing
these mainframes.

00:29:41.670 --> 00:29:42.640
This is the mainframe market.

00:29:42.640 --> 00:29:43.220
This isn't the PC market.

00:29:43.220 --> 00:29:44.470
This is the mainframe market.

00:29:44.470 --> 00:29:47.300
In the mainframe market, now
people don't want mainframes

00:29:47.300 --> 00:29:49.090
much anymore.

00:29:49.090 --> 00:29:50.640
But there were a lot
of firms producing.

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:52.420
There was IBM and tons of other
firms producing these

00:29:52.420 --> 00:29:52.820
mainframes.

00:29:52.820 --> 00:29:53.890
Because that's what
everybody wanted.

00:29:53.890 --> 00:29:57.820
So the original supply curve
was very flat at SR1.

00:29:57.820 --> 00:29:59.540
So, initially, in the mainframe
market, we're in

00:29:59.540 --> 00:30:07.840
equilibrium with quantity Q1--
big Q1-- and a price P1.

00:30:07.840 --> 00:30:09.380
And what's happening there?

00:30:09.380 --> 00:30:11.740
Where does that price intersect
marginal cost?

00:30:11.740 --> 00:30:16.070
It intersects marginal cost for
IBM at little q1 which is

00:30:16.070 --> 00:30:21.586
below average total cost.
So IBM is losing money.

00:30:21.586 --> 00:30:24.950
In the initial short run
equilibrium, IBM is producing

00:30:24.950 --> 00:30:28.120
at little q1, and it's
losing money.

00:30:28.120 --> 00:30:29.580
Now, why is it still
in business?

00:30:29.580 --> 00:30:30.730
Because it's the short run.

00:30:30.730 --> 00:30:33.340
And as long as those losses are
less than its fixed cost,

00:30:33.340 --> 00:30:35.410
it's staying in business.

00:30:35.410 --> 00:30:38.010
So, in the short run,
you can lose money.

00:30:38.010 --> 00:30:39.300
So IBM is losing money.

00:30:39.300 --> 00:30:41.050
Because it's built
this big plant.

00:30:41.050 --> 00:30:42.700
It's cranking out these
mainframes.

00:30:42.700 --> 00:30:43.750
People don't want
them anymore.

00:30:43.750 --> 00:30:48.580
The price has fallen so low
that they can still make

00:30:48.580 --> 00:30:51.990
enough money than it costs to
produce the next mainframe.

00:30:51.990 --> 00:30:55.480
Price is still greater than
marginal costs, but price is

00:30:55.480 --> 00:30:58.540
below average costs.

00:30:58.540 --> 00:30:59.070
I'm sorry.

00:30:59.070 --> 00:31:00.555
Prices are greater than average
variable cost. But

00:31:00.555 --> 00:31:02.880
it's lower the total average
cost. They're losing money.

00:31:02.880 --> 00:31:03.770
So what happens?

00:31:03.770 --> 00:31:06.370
They leave.

00:31:06.370 --> 00:31:07.790
There was a company
called [? Deck ?]

00:31:07.790 --> 00:31:10.590
that went out of business.

00:31:10.590 --> 00:31:14.760
And what happened was that then
raised the supply curve.

00:31:14.760 --> 00:31:17.800
It steepened the supply curve
in the mainframe market.

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:23.230
It steepened the supply curve,
because now you have fewer

00:31:23.230 --> 00:31:25.200
firms producing mainframes.

00:31:25.200 --> 00:31:26.390
That supply curve
gets steeper.

00:31:26.390 --> 00:31:28.420
That raises the price.

00:31:28.420 --> 00:31:32.040
And, indeed, exit will continue
until you raise the

00:31:32.040 --> 00:31:35.620
price to the point where
marginal cost equals average

00:31:35.620 --> 00:31:38.270
total cost.

00:31:38.270 --> 00:31:41.500
And what you'll see is the
market will shrink from

00:31:41.500 --> 00:31:43.150
big Q1 to big Q2.

00:31:43.150 --> 00:31:46.000
The remaining market
participants will increase

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:49.310
from little q1 to little q2.

00:31:49.310 --> 00:31:54.110
And profits go to 0 with price
going to the minimum average

00:31:54.110 --> 00:31:58.830
cost. So through both entry
and exit, we get this

00:31:58.830 --> 00:32:04.690
condition that's illustrated
in Figure 11-5.

00:32:04.690 --> 00:32:11.220
In 11-5, we see that in the long
run, firms always supply

00:32:11.220 --> 00:32:15.500
not on a single curve but
at a single point.

00:32:15.500 --> 00:32:19.220
In the long run, with a
perfectly competitive market,

00:32:19.220 --> 00:32:22.290
for a given firm, there is no
longer even meaningfully a

00:32:22.290 --> 00:32:23.900
supply curve to a firm.

00:32:23.900 --> 00:32:26.810
There's just literally
a supply point.

00:32:26.810 --> 00:32:30.390
Every firm produces at exactly
the point where marginal costs

00:32:30.390 --> 00:32:32.600
equal average costs.

00:32:32.600 --> 00:32:35.860
So in some sense, once again,
for a given firm--

00:32:35.860 --> 00:32:39.010
this is not the market-- but for
a given firm, there's not

00:32:39.010 --> 00:32:41.440
even meaningfully a supply
curve anymore.

00:32:41.440 --> 00:32:44.430
For a given firm, in the long
run, they literally choose one

00:32:44.430 --> 00:32:48.220
production point which is
technologically given.

00:32:48.220 --> 00:32:49.330
So this is interesting.

00:32:49.330 --> 00:32:52.900
For a given firm, the market
doesn't matter.

00:32:52.900 --> 00:32:54.550
For a given firm in a perfectly
competitive market,

00:32:54.550 --> 00:32:57.350
we don't need to know anything
about demand.

00:32:57.350 --> 00:33:00.520
All we need to know is the
firm's production function.

00:33:00.520 --> 00:33:01.210
That's all we need to know.

00:33:01.210 --> 00:33:03.735
We don't even need to know
anything about costs.

00:33:03.735 --> 00:33:07.960
Well, we need to know
cost. We need to

00:33:07.960 --> 00:33:09.040
know their cost function.

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:11.380
All we need to know is
their cost function.

00:33:11.380 --> 00:33:14.270
And then all we need to do is
derive where marginal costs

00:33:14.270 --> 00:33:17.140
equals average costs,
and we're done.

00:33:17.140 --> 00:33:18.650
This is the power of the
perfectly competitive

00:33:18.650 --> 00:33:19.150
equilibrium.

00:33:19.150 --> 00:33:21.120
This is why economists
love it so much.

00:33:21.120 --> 00:33:23.830
Because we don't need to
go through all this.

00:33:23.830 --> 00:33:24.910
This is all short run stuff.

00:33:24.910 --> 00:33:26.010
In the long run, it's easy.

00:33:26.010 --> 00:33:27.661
You just say, give me a cost
function, I'll tell you what

00:33:27.661 --> 00:33:29.160
the firm will produce.

00:33:29.160 --> 00:33:31.270
And I'll tell you what
the price is.

00:33:31.270 --> 00:33:33.200
The firm will produce where
marginal cost equals average

00:33:33.200 --> 00:33:35.400
cost. And the price will be
where marginal cost equals

00:33:35.400 --> 00:33:36.460
average costs.

00:33:36.460 --> 00:33:39.300
I can tell you the p and the q
in equilibrium just if you

00:33:39.300 --> 00:33:40.880
give me a cost function.

00:33:40.880 --> 00:33:43.950
And that's the beauty of the
long run perfectly competitive

00:33:43.950 --> 00:33:44.310
equilibrium.

00:33:44.310 --> 00:33:46.290
That's why it's so attractive
to economists for modeling

00:33:46.290 --> 00:33:47.590
purposes and other things.

00:33:47.590 --> 00:33:50.150
It's incredibly easy
to work with.

00:33:50.150 --> 00:33:55.090
Because all you need is a cost
function, and you're done.

00:33:55.090 --> 00:33:59.430
The key lesson is what is true
at the point where marginal

00:33:59.430 --> 00:34:01.950
costs equals average costs?

00:34:01.950 --> 00:34:03.910
Well, look at our graph.

00:34:03.910 --> 00:34:08.090
That is the point of
cost minimization.

00:34:08.090 --> 00:34:11.730
Note that that is the very
minimum point of the long run

00:34:11.730 --> 00:34:13.250
average cost curve.

00:34:13.250 --> 00:34:17.940
So where marginal cost equals
average cost is the point of

00:34:17.940 --> 00:34:19.190
cost minimization.

00:34:21.719 --> 00:34:23.320
So we're saying further--

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:24.780
this is even more powerful--

00:34:24.780 --> 00:34:27.120
we're saying that in the long
run of perfectly competitive

00:34:27.120 --> 00:34:29.440
equilibrium firms will,
by definition,

00:34:29.440 --> 00:34:31.050
minimize their costs.

00:34:31.050 --> 00:34:34.830
They will produce as efficiently
as possible not

00:34:34.830 --> 00:34:36.900
because God told them
to, but through the

00:34:36.900 --> 00:34:39.300
power of the market.

00:34:39.300 --> 00:34:41.940
Because what happens if you
start a firm and you aren't

00:34:41.940 --> 00:34:43.900
cost minimizing?

00:34:43.900 --> 00:34:45.010
What happens?

00:34:45.010 --> 00:34:48.114
What happens is, in the short
run, you might make money even

00:34:48.114 --> 00:34:49.880
if you aren't cost minimizing.

00:34:49.880 --> 00:34:52.750
But, in long run, you'll get
driven out of business.

00:34:52.750 --> 00:34:55.300
Because if there's someone
else who can produce more

00:34:55.300 --> 00:34:59.150
cheaply than you, they'll be
able to charge a lower price

00:34:59.150 --> 00:35:00.480
and drive you out of business.

00:35:00.480 --> 00:35:03.020
Your price will end up above the
long run equilibrium price

00:35:03.020 --> 00:35:04.940
if you're not cost minimizing.

00:35:04.940 --> 00:35:08.090
So any firm that is not cost
minimizing will get driven out

00:35:08.090 --> 00:35:09.520
of business.

00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:13.540
And the equilibrium will be a
market where all firms are

00:35:13.540 --> 00:35:16.570
producing at the cost
minimizing level.

00:35:16.570 --> 00:35:21.830
And that's why we get the high
tech Figure 11-6, which is

00:35:21.830 --> 00:35:24.580
that the long run market
supply curve

00:35:24.580 --> 00:35:25.830
is perfectly elastic.

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:31.910
Now this comes all the way back
to what I talked about at

00:35:31.910 --> 00:35:33.700
the beginning of the
last lecture.

00:35:33.700 --> 00:35:35.960
Remember I said, what
determines perfect

00:35:35.960 --> 00:35:36.620
competition?

00:35:36.620 --> 00:35:41.300
Two things, the demand curve
to the firm was perfectly

00:35:41.300 --> 00:35:46.120
elastic, and the supply
curve to the market

00:35:46.120 --> 00:35:49.350
is perfectly elastic.

00:35:49.350 --> 00:35:51.670
And we talked last time about
why the demand curve to the

00:35:51.670 --> 00:35:52.660
firm is perfectly elastic.

00:35:52.660 --> 00:35:54.900
Because with lots of firms, any
given firm has a perfectly

00:35:54.900 --> 00:35:56.160
elastic demand.

00:35:56.160 --> 00:35:58.940
Now we've just derived why the
market supply curve is

00:35:58.940 --> 00:36:01.090
perfectly elastic.

00:36:01.090 --> 00:36:05.650
It's perfectly elastic at the
cost minimizing point.

00:36:05.650 --> 00:36:08.790
If the price ever rises above
that cost minimizing point,

00:36:08.790 --> 00:36:11.350
what happens?

00:36:11.350 --> 00:36:15.910
What happens if the price should
suddenly rise above it?

00:36:15.910 --> 00:36:17.402
What happens?

00:36:17.402 --> 00:36:21.720
Firms enter and drive
the price back down.

00:36:21.720 --> 00:36:24.670
If the price ever drops below
that cost minimizing point,

00:36:24.670 --> 00:36:27.610
firms exit, and the price
goes back up.

00:36:27.610 --> 00:36:30.760
So through the power of firm
entry and exit, in the long

00:36:30.760 --> 00:36:35.400
run, you end up with a
horizontal or perfectly

00:36:35.400 --> 00:36:37.560
elastic supply curve.

00:36:37.560 --> 00:36:38.810
And that's perfect
competition.

00:36:41.600 --> 00:36:43.037
Questions about that?

00:36:43.037 --> 00:36:44.031
Yeah?

00:36:44.031 --> 00:36:49.001
AUDIENCE: You said that if it's
not profit maximizing,

00:36:49.001 --> 00:36:51.983
then it cannot
[INAUDIBLE PHRASE].

00:36:51.983 --> 00:36:54.970
But [INAUDIBLE PHRASE].

00:36:54.970 --> 00:36:55.530
PROFESSOR: Yes, they are.

00:36:55.530 --> 00:36:56.570
So that's a great point.

00:36:56.570 --> 00:36:59.280
So what will happen is it's not
that a firm will charge a

00:36:59.280 --> 00:37:00.110
lower price.

00:37:00.110 --> 00:37:01.140
I shouldn't have said
it that way.

00:37:01.140 --> 00:37:03.150
It's that another
firm will enter.

00:37:03.150 --> 00:37:05.140
And, by definition, the price
will then fall, because the

00:37:05.140 --> 00:37:08.170
supply curve will flatten, and
the price will then fall.

00:37:08.170 --> 00:37:10.490
So if you're in there producing
inefficiently and I

00:37:10.490 --> 00:37:12.690
say, hey, your firm sucks.

00:37:12.690 --> 00:37:15.050
I can come in and produce much
more efficiently than you.

00:37:15.050 --> 00:37:17.740
I'll hop in, that will flatten
the supply curve.

00:37:17.740 --> 00:37:18.800
The price will fall.

00:37:18.800 --> 00:37:22.300
At that price, if I'm
not cost minimizing,

00:37:22.300 --> 00:37:23.310
I'll be losing money.

00:37:23.310 --> 00:37:26.070
So I'll leave.

00:37:26.070 --> 00:37:27.770
That's a good clarifying
question.

00:37:27.770 --> 00:37:31.080
So if we have a market with a
bunch of guys in it, and one

00:37:31.080 --> 00:37:34.100
of them is not cost minimizing,
well, that means

00:37:34.100 --> 00:37:36.390
someone else can come in.

00:37:36.390 --> 00:37:39.640
They'll, in the short run,
expand the market.

00:37:39.640 --> 00:37:43.040
That will flatten the supply
curve, drive the price down.

00:37:43.040 --> 00:37:45.490
At that lower price, the
non-cost maximizing firm says,

00:37:45.490 --> 00:37:46.060
I'm losing money.

00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:47.410
So I leave.

00:37:47.410 --> 00:37:49.610
The price goes back up, and it
goes up and down and up and

00:37:49.610 --> 00:37:51.250
down until it settles
at this point

00:37:51.250 --> 00:37:54.640
where costs are minimized.

00:37:54.640 --> 00:37:57.945
So perfect competition leads to
a perfectly elastic supply

00:37:57.945 --> 00:37:59.195
and cost minimization.

00:38:01.460 --> 00:38:04.300
So that is our extreme.

00:38:04.300 --> 00:38:08.950
That is the theoretical
point of no return.

00:38:08.950 --> 00:38:11.710
Of course, in reality,
we never get there.

00:38:11.710 --> 00:38:14.270
In reality, there's no such
thing as a purely perfectly

00:38:14.270 --> 00:38:17.410
competitive equilibrium.

00:38:17.410 --> 00:38:18.300
Why not?

00:38:18.300 --> 00:38:23.950
Well, in the long run, supply
is actually upward sloping.

00:38:23.950 --> 00:38:27.270
In the long run, market supply
will be upward sloping.

00:38:27.270 --> 00:38:30.640
And that's going to be for
at least three reasons.

00:38:30.640 --> 00:38:33.810
So why is long run supply upward
sloping in reality?

00:38:45.100 --> 00:38:47.350
Well, in reality, if would be
for at least three reasons.

00:38:47.350 --> 00:38:51.180
The first reason is that entry
and exit are not free.

00:38:51.180 --> 00:38:58.410
There could be barriers
to entry or exit.

00:38:58.410 --> 00:39:01.650
Even in the long run, there
could be barriers

00:39:01.650 --> 00:39:04.220
to entry and exit.

00:39:04.220 --> 00:39:07.110
There could be features of the
market which make it hard to

00:39:07.110 --> 00:39:09.590
leave or hard to join.

00:39:09.590 --> 00:39:12.870
A classic example is something
that we introduced a couple

00:39:12.870 --> 00:39:17.500
lectures ago, the notion of sunk
costs, costs which even

00:39:17.500 --> 00:39:19.750
in the long run might
be fixed.

00:39:26.850 --> 00:39:30.380
If they're large sunk costs, if
one firm's incurred them,

00:39:30.380 --> 00:39:32.480
another firm is going to say,
look, it's not worth it

00:39:32.480 --> 00:39:33.730
for me to get in.

00:39:36.990 --> 00:39:40.470
If you have to build such a
massive plant to produce your

00:39:40.470 --> 00:39:43.160
good, then it takes an
unbelievable amount of

00:39:43.160 --> 00:39:45.560
capital, it's a huge investment,
and once you're

00:39:45.560 --> 00:39:48.670
in, it's going to be really hard
to drive you out, because

00:39:48.670 --> 00:39:50.590
you made that big investment,
other firms

00:39:50.590 --> 00:39:52.670
might say, forget it.

00:39:52.670 --> 00:39:55.080
Dell made this huge investment
in this huge plant.

00:39:55.080 --> 00:39:56.730
They're never going to leave
having built that plant.

00:39:56.730 --> 00:39:59.180
That's virtually a sunk cost.
So I'm not even going to

00:39:59.180 --> 00:40:00.590
bother entering.

00:40:00.590 --> 00:40:02.580
So Dell can exist making
some profit, maybe

00:40:02.580 --> 00:40:03.570
not too much profit.

00:40:03.570 --> 00:40:05.470
If they make too much profit,
then another firm

00:40:05.470 --> 00:40:07.230
will build a plant.

00:40:07.230 --> 00:40:09.040
Well, as long as they're not
making too much profit, they

00:40:09.040 --> 00:40:09.950
can make some profit.

00:40:09.950 --> 00:40:11.590
Because another firm says,
you know what, I

00:40:11.590 --> 00:40:12.500
can't fight that battle.

00:40:12.500 --> 00:40:14.640
I can't build a plant
that big.

00:40:14.640 --> 00:40:17.300
Or there could be other
things like that.

00:40:23.170 --> 00:40:24.660
That's sort of a natural
barrier to entry.

00:40:24.660 --> 00:40:26.580
There are some artificial
barriers to entry we see.

00:40:26.580 --> 00:40:31.120
For example, take med school.

00:40:31.120 --> 00:40:34.330
The number of slots to be
doctors is limited by the

00:40:34.330 --> 00:40:35.740
physician profession.

00:40:35.740 --> 00:40:38.230
So even if docs make lots of
money, which they do--

00:40:38.230 --> 00:40:39.730
especially specialists--

00:40:39.730 --> 00:40:42.120
you can't just compete and
have new doctors enter.

00:40:42.120 --> 00:40:44.070
Because the number of slots
are actually limited.

00:40:44.070 --> 00:40:46.760
You have to be licensed by an
organization which is run by

00:40:46.760 --> 00:40:48.660
the people making
all the money.

00:40:48.660 --> 00:40:51.320
So if you're a doc, and
you're in, this is

00:40:51.320 --> 00:40:52.180
a pretty good deal.

00:40:52.180 --> 00:40:53.390
You say, hey, let's have
a system where new

00:40:53.390 --> 00:40:54.950
docs can't be licensed.

00:40:54.950 --> 00:40:56.240
They'll have to come
to me, and I can

00:40:56.240 --> 00:40:57.560
charge whatever I want.

00:40:57.560 --> 00:40:58.490
That's a barrier to entry.

00:40:58.490 --> 00:41:00.400
We call that occupational
licensing.

00:41:00.400 --> 00:41:01.460
We see that in lots
of professions.

00:41:01.460 --> 00:41:04.390
Plumbing, taxi drivers,
we see it everywhere.

00:41:04.390 --> 00:41:07.420
It's occupational licensing.

00:41:07.420 --> 00:41:09.180
A second example, of
course, is patents.

00:41:09.180 --> 00:41:11.660
And we'll talk about patents
more in a few lectures.

00:41:11.660 --> 00:41:15.160
If I invented a new drug, and
it's patented, nobody can sell

00:41:15.160 --> 00:41:17.770
that same chemical compound
for 17 years.

00:41:17.770 --> 00:41:20.620
That's a barrier to entry.

00:41:20.620 --> 00:41:22.890
There could be more informal
barriers to entry.

00:41:22.890 --> 00:41:26.150
Let's say you're around Port
Authority setting up these

00:41:26.150 --> 00:41:27.680
little shlocky stands, the
ones we said were perfect

00:41:27.680 --> 00:41:29.720
competition.

00:41:29.720 --> 00:41:31.650
You've got yours, and the guy
comes in next to you, you just

00:41:31.650 --> 00:41:33.710
beat the crap out out of him.

00:41:33.710 --> 00:41:35.190
That's an informal
barrier to entry.

00:41:35.190 --> 00:41:38.120
You say, you come in, and you're
going to get beaten up.

00:41:38.120 --> 00:41:40.320
The guy says, well look, if it's
a big profit, it's worth

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:41.390
getting beaten up.

00:41:41.390 --> 00:41:42.970
Or I'll hire protection
if it's a big profit.

00:41:42.970 --> 00:41:44.160
But it's not that big of a
profit, I'm not going to

00:41:44.160 --> 00:41:45.670
bother getting beaten
up over it.

00:41:45.670 --> 00:41:46.690
So I'll let you make
your profit.

00:41:46.690 --> 00:41:48.110
I won't come in.

00:41:48.110 --> 00:41:50.780
So barriers to entry exist
all over the place.

00:41:50.780 --> 00:41:53.250
And they're a big reason why
we don't get a perfectly

00:41:53.250 --> 00:41:56.620
elastic supply curve in most
markets because of things like

00:41:56.620 --> 00:41:59.540
patents or thuggery.

00:41:59.540 --> 00:42:02.820
So that's one example of
why you don't get it.

00:42:02.820 --> 00:42:04.880
Another example of why you
might not get a perfectly

00:42:04.880 --> 00:42:11.960
elastic supply curve is that
firms might differ.

00:42:11.960 --> 00:42:15.150
In particular, we have assumed
critically, through the last

00:42:15.150 --> 00:42:18.870
lecture and this lecture, that
firms are identical.

00:42:18.870 --> 00:42:19.970
We have assumed that firms
are identical.

00:42:19.970 --> 00:42:22.560
But, in fact, of course,
firms aren't.

00:42:22.560 --> 00:42:25.770
And one firm's cost minimizing
production level might be

00:42:25.770 --> 00:42:27.040
different than another
firm's cost

00:42:27.040 --> 00:42:28.810
minimizing production level.

00:42:28.810 --> 00:42:30.900
Not all firms will have
exactly the same cost

00:42:30.900 --> 00:42:32.590
minimizing production level.

00:42:32.590 --> 00:42:36.430
In particular, some firms may
have a lower minimum average

00:42:36.430 --> 00:42:39.480
cost than others for a while.

00:42:39.480 --> 00:42:41.740
So it may be that as long as
I'm producing less than x

00:42:41.740 --> 00:42:47.080
units, I have a lower minimum
average cost than you do.

00:42:47.080 --> 00:42:49.710
But once I produce more than x
units, my minimum average cost

00:42:49.710 --> 00:42:51.900
rises to above yours.

00:42:51.900 --> 00:42:56.780
Well, in that case, I might be
able to make money for a while

00:42:56.780 --> 00:42:57.410
staying in.

00:42:57.410 --> 00:42:59.480
But then once I produce too
much, I'm going to have to

00:42:59.480 --> 00:43:00.900
raise the price.

00:43:00.900 --> 00:43:04.550
So to see this, there's a great
example in Perloff which

00:43:04.550 --> 00:43:07.170
you see in Figure 11-7, where
he talks about the

00:43:07.170 --> 00:43:10.940
international long run market
supply curve for cotton.

00:43:10.940 --> 00:43:16.540
And he says, look, in Pakistan,
you can produce

00:43:16.540 --> 00:43:18.350
cotton incredibly cheaply.

00:43:18.350 --> 00:43:20.500
This is a dated example, but in
Pakistan, you can produce

00:43:20.500 --> 00:43:22.080
cotton incredibly cheaply.

00:43:22.080 --> 00:43:26.960
You can produce it at
$0.71 per kilogram.

00:43:26.960 --> 00:43:32.190
So if the world demand for
cotton is less than $2 billion

00:43:32.190 --> 00:43:34.990
kilograms per year, or less than
$1.8 billion kilograms

00:43:34.990 --> 00:43:39.400
per year, then Pakistan would
provide it all, and the price

00:43:39.400 --> 00:43:42.290
would be $0.71.

00:43:42.290 --> 00:43:43.900
But let's say the demand
is more than that.

00:43:43.900 --> 00:43:46.290
Well, Pakistan just runs
out of cotton.

00:43:46.290 --> 00:43:46.880
They can't do that.

00:43:46.880 --> 00:43:48.450
Well, then you have to go to
the next cheapest country.

00:43:48.450 --> 00:43:50.110
Well, the next cheapest
country is Argentina.

00:43:50.110 --> 00:43:53.100
It costs a lot more to
produce cotton there.

00:43:53.100 --> 00:43:55.240
And then comes Australia,
Brazil, Nicaragua, Turkey,

00:43:55.240 --> 00:43:56.060
then finally the US.

00:43:56.060 --> 00:43:59.380
And then Iran is the
most expensive.

00:43:59.380 --> 00:44:02.460
So this is, effectively, an
upward sloping supply curve.

00:44:02.460 --> 00:44:05.340
It's stepwise, but it's an
upward sloping supply in the

00:44:05.340 --> 00:44:10.980
sense that as you want more
quantity, the price goes up.

00:44:10.980 --> 00:44:14.750
So if the market wants $5
billion kilograms of cotton a

00:44:14.750 --> 00:44:19.000
year, then that means that the
marginal producer is the US

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:22.940
even though they're much less
efficient than Pakistan.

00:44:22.940 --> 00:44:25.370
Because Pakistan hit
a constraint.

00:44:25.370 --> 00:44:28.340
You have to go to that next
less efficient producer.

00:44:28.340 --> 00:44:32.190
So that's taking an upward
sloping supply curve.

00:44:32.190 --> 00:44:35.340
Basically you're getting an
upward sloping supply curve,

00:44:35.340 --> 00:44:37.380
because you have constraints
on how much any

00:44:37.380 --> 00:44:39.380
given firm can produce.

00:44:39.380 --> 00:44:42.570
Those constraints can make you
move onto less efficient firms

00:44:42.570 --> 00:44:44.360
as you go on.

00:44:44.360 --> 00:44:46.440
And so in a market, you'll end
up, in reality, with a

00:44:46.440 --> 00:44:48.670
distribution of firms
ranging from most

00:44:48.670 --> 00:44:50.970
efficient to least efficient.

00:44:50.970 --> 00:44:52.740
The most efficient would produce
as much as it can at

00:44:52.740 --> 00:44:53.760
that efficiency level.

00:44:53.760 --> 00:44:55.660
But then some less efficient
ones will get in the game as

00:44:55.660 --> 00:44:57.690
well just depending on
where demand is.

00:44:57.690 --> 00:44:59.540
So you can see if you put in
demand curves at different

00:44:59.540 --> 00:45:02.070
points in the supply curve,
you get different prices.

00:45:02.070 --> 00:45:04.970
That's an upward sloping
supply curve.

00:45:04.970 --> 00:45:07.810
That's a second reason.

00:45:07.810 --> 00:45:09.350
And then a third reason--

00:45:09.350 --> 00:45:11.680
these aren't a comprehensive
list, but types of reasons why

00:45:11.680 --> 00:45:13.870
supply curves will slope
up in reality--

00:45:13.870 --> 00:45:19.610
is that input prices might rise
as the market expands.

00:45:19.610 --> 00:45:21.400
We've assumed fixed
input prices.

00:45:21.400 --> 00:45:25.300
I gave you an r and w, and
I assume they were fixed.

00:45:25.300 --> 00:45:27.640
But, in fact, that might
not be true.

00:45:27.640 --> 00:45:32.470
It might be that, in reality,
as you want to produce more,

00:45:32.470 --> 00:45:34.690
you need to buy more
of the input.

00:45:34.690 --> 00:45:36.650
Well, if you need to buy more
of the input, and the input

00:45:36.650 --> 00:45:39.320
has an upward sloping supply
curve, then you'll have to pay

00:45:39.320 --> 00:45:41.030
more to get more
of that input.

00:45:41.030 --> 00:45:44.260
So to see that, let's run
through an example.

00:45:44.260 --> 00:45:47.550
Let's imagine that you want to
produce something in the long

00:45:47.550 --> 00:45:50.690
run, and you need more
labor to produce it.

00:45:50.690 --> 00:45:52.570
So as you produce more of
it, you need more labor.

00:45:55.860 --> 00:45:57.860
So now let's go to
Figure 11-8.

00:45:57.860 --> 00:46:01.050
You're initially, in your firm,
demanding L1 units of

00:46:01.050 --> 00:46:03.990
labor at a the wage of W1.

00:46:03.990 --> 00:46:07.570
And let's say that at that
point, at that wage, you're

00:46:07.570 --> 00:46:09.160
cost minimizing.

00:46:09.160 --> 00:46:12.320
That's the cost minimizing
point, and you've got this

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:15.210
flat supply curve.

00:46:15.210 --> 00:46:15.900
You're at that point.

00:46:15.900 --> 00:46:17.800
Now let's say you want
to produce more.

00:46:17.800 --> 00:46:19.615
Well, to produce more, you've
got to go to the market and

00:46:19.615 --> 00:46:20.830
hire more labor.

00:46:20.830 --> 00:46:24.940
If the supply curve for labor is
upward sloping, if labor is

00:46:24.940 --> 00:46:27.550
not a perfectly competitive
market and, therefore, is an

00:46:27.550 --> 00:46:29.330
upward sloping supply,
they'll say, fine.

00:46:29.330 --> 00:46:30.520
If you want more workers,
you've got to pay more.

00:46:30.520 --> 00:46:32.410
You've got to pay W2.

00:46:32.410 --> 00:46:34.590
You've got to pay more
for your workers.

00:46:34.590 --> 00:46:35.920
Well, think about
what that does.

00:46:35.920 --> 00:46:38.030
Now, go to Figure 11-9.

00:46:38.030 --> 00:46:45.730
What that means is that as I
produce more units, I have to

00:46:45.730 --> 00:46:48.300
pay more for the labor.

00:46:48.300 --> 00:46:50.460
Now let's start on the left-hand
side figure.

00:46:50.460 --> 00:46:56.000
That says that if I'm producing
little q1 as a firm,

00:46:56.000 --> 00:46:58.230
my marginal cost is MC super
1, and my average

00:46:58.230 --> 00:46:59.990
cost is AC super 1.

00:46:59.990 --> 00:47:02.370
So I'm at P1.

00:47:02.370 --> 00:47:08.230
Now if I want to produce more,
if I want to produce q2, my

00:47:08.230 --> 00:47:10.560
average cost is going to be
higher, and my marginal cost

00:47:10.560 --> 00:47:11.690
is going to be higher, because
I have to pay a

00:47:11.690 --> 00:47:13.790
higher wage to workers.

00:47:13.790 --> 00:47:15.650
So that's going to shift
me up to have to

00:47:15.650 --> 00:47:18.770
charge a higher price.

00:47:18.770 --> 00:47:20.720
Now, I'm still cost
minimizing.

00:47:20.720 --> 00:47:23.420
Given the wage the market
gives me, I'm still cost

00:47:23.420 --> 00:47:23.620
minimizing.

00:47:23.620 --> 00:47:25.520
There's nothing non-cost
minimizing about this.

00:47:25.520 --> 00:47:27.180
I'm still cost minimizing.

00:47:27.180 --> 00:47:29.730
But to cost minimize, I
have to charge more.

00:47:29.730 --> 00:47:32.600
Because the market's charging
me a higher price.

00:47:32.600 --> 00:47:36.890
If you go back to solving our
initial production decision,

00:47:36.890 --> 00:47:39.360
you'll see that because this is
a higher wage, that's going

00:47:39.360 --> 00:47:42.060
to shift my cost function up.

00:47:42.060 --> 00:47:44.070
A high wage is going to
make my costs higher.

00:47:44.070 --> 00:47:47.450
That's going to make my cost
minimizing price be higher.

00:47:47.450 --> 00:47:49.030
So I'm going to shift.

00:47:49.030 --> 00:47:50.520
I'm going to need to charge
a higher price.

00:47:50.520 --> 00:47:53.050
That, itself, will also
yield an upward

00:47:53.050 --> 00:47:55.530
sloping supply curve.

00:47:55.530 --> 00:47:59.820
So an upward sloping supply
curve comes from the fact that

00:47:59.820 --> 00:48:02.510
as I produce more, I've
got to pay higher

00:48:02.510 --> 00:48:03.870
prices for my inputs.

00:48:03.870 --> 00:48:05.910
That means I've got to charge
higher prices for my outputs.

00:48:08.560 --> 00:48:12.310
So these are three examples of
reasons why, in reality, we

00:48:12.310 --> 00:48:15.550
don't see a perfectly flat
long run supply curve.

00:48:15.550 --> 00:48:19.490
So once again, to review,
because this is the end of

00:48:19.490 --> 00:48:23.660
this particular topic, to review
where we are, the way

00:48:23.660 --> 00:48:25.940
it works is firms are given
a cost function.

00:48:25.940 --> 00:48:28.810
Well, they choose
a technology.

00:48:28.810 --> 00:48:30.390
That gives them a
cost function.

00:48:30.390 --> 00:48:31.800
They enter the market.

00:48:31.800 --> 00:48:35.250
In the short run, they're stuck
with that technology.

00:48:35.250 --> 00:48:37.860
So they decide to produce where
price equals marginal

00:48:37.860 --> 00:48:39.830
cost as long as they're not
losing more money than they've

00:48:39.830 --> 00:48:41.600
paid in fixed costs.

00:48:41.600 --> 00:48:45.440
In the long run, firms come in
and out until the point where

00:48:45.440 --> 00:48:48.530
every firm is producing
efficiently.

00:48:48.530 --> 00:48:51.110
As long as entry is free, as
long as there are not barriers

00:48:51.110 --> 00:48:54.910
to entry, every firm is
producing efficiently.

00:48:57.640 --> 00:48:59.410
Then every firm is producing
at a single point, which is

00:48:59.410 --> 00:49:02.700
where marginal cost equals
average cost. That yields a

00:49:02.700 --> 00:49:07.080
flat long run supply curve at
the technological minimum.

00:49:07.080 --> 00:49:10.540
In reality, supply curves slope
up because there might

00:49:10.540 --> 00:49:13.470
be barriers to entry which
leads to non-cost

00:49:13.470 --> 00:49:14.720
minimization.

00:49:20.540 --> 00:49:22.040
So this leads to non-cost
minimization.

00:49:24.630 --> 00:49:26.700
And then there's two reasons,
even if you're cost

00:49:26.700 --> 00:49:31.480
minimizing, you still could
have capacity constraints,

00:49:31.480 --> 00:49:38.480
which is like our cotton
example, or you could have

00:49:38.480 --> 00:49:40.210
upward sloping input supply.

00:49:47.810 --> 00:49:51.540
So that's why, in reality, we
draw the upward sloping supply

00:49:51.540 --> 00:49:53.720
curves that we started with at
the beginning of this course

00:49:53.720 --> 00:49:56.550
even with a perfectly
competitive market.

00:49:56.550 --> 00:49:58.140
So let's stop there.

00:49:58.140 --> 00:50:00.520
That's a lot of stuff to digest.
We're going to come

00:50:00.520 --> 00:50:03.100
back next time and talk about
why all this is crap, and

00:50:03.100 --> 00:50:05.240
firms don't really cost minimize
or maximize profits

00:50:05.240 --> 00:50:06.490
or any of that.